The start symbol S can expand in only two ways:

1. S → NT119 NT57  
   NT57 → NT74 NT4 → t270 t353  
   Therefore this branch would place the contiguous pair “t270 t353” somewhere in the string.  
   The given string contains “t270” (position 6) and “t353” (position 25), but they are not adjacent, so this branch cannot produce the string.

2. S → NT72 NT90  
   NT90 must eventually produce either  
   • NT83 NT4 (ending with NT4 → t353) or  
   • NT118 NT117 (ending with NT117 → t334).  
   In both cases the substring generated by NT90 must end with either “t353” or “t334”.  
   In the given string the only “t353” appears at position 25 and is followed by seven further tokens, so no suffix of the string ends with a single final “t353”.  
   The token “t334” does not occur at all.  
   Consequently NT90 cannot match any suffix of the string, so this second branch also fails.

Since neither of the only two possible expansions of S can cover the required terminal sequence, the string is not in the language of the grammar.

No

To obtain the whole string S must begin with one of its only two possibilities  

 S → NT119 NT57 or S → NT72 NT90.  

In both cases the second symbol ultimately contains the fixed non-terminal NT4 which is the
only producer of the terminal  t309 :

 NT57 → NT74 NT4    NT90 → NT83 NT4    NT4 → 't309'

Hence the last word of every sentence in the language must be t309 (which agrees with the
given string).  
The word that immediately precedes t309 must come from NT74 (if the first production is
used) or from NT83 (if the second production is used).  We examine these two non-terminals.

1.  NT74  
 NT74 has only the productions  
  NT74 → 't270'  or  NT74 → NT68 NT116  
 So NT74 can yield either the single terminal t270, or at least two terminals (because both
NT68 and NT116 must each produce at least one terminal).  
 Therefore NT74 can never generate exactly one terminal different from t270. In particular it
can never end with the single terminal t84, which is the item that immediately precedes the
final t309 in the given string.

2.  NT83  
 NT83 has only the productions  
  NT83 → NT111 NT110  or  NT83 → NT86 NT25  
 Inspecting every possibility for the right–hand non-terminal in those rules shows the last
terminal NT83 can produce is one of  
 t309, t319, t274, t347, t242, t334, t353, t108 – never t84.  
 Hence NT83 likewise cannot end with t84.

Because the token just before the final t309 in the supplied string is t84, neither
NT74 NT4 nor NT83 NT4 can match the suffix “… t84 t309”.  Consequently neither
NT119 NT57 nor NT72 NT90 can derive the whole string, so the start symbol S cannot
generate it.

Answer: No

The last symbol of the string is `t309`.  
In the grammar the only production that can emit this terminal is

  NT4 → 't309'.

Therefore the right–most variable in any successful derivation must be NT4.

Scanning the grammar, NT4 appears on the right-hand side only in the following binary rules (always as the second symbol):

 NT57 → NT74 NT4  
 NT90 → NT83 NT4  
 NT110 → NT120 NT4

Consequently, just before the final `t309` the string must contain the word(s) produced by NT74, NT83 or NT120 respectively.

What can these non-terminals generate?

• NT74 → 't270'                 (one word)  
    | NT68 NT116           (two words)

 Possible words emitted by NT68: t323, t390, t107  
 Possible word emitted by NT116: t6  
 So NT74 can end with t270 or with the sequence “… t6”.

• NT83 → NT111 NT110 or NT86 NT25  
 Both alternatives always yield at least two words, and the very last word they
 produce can only be one of  
  t242, t347, t319, t274, t399, t79, t183, t353, t108, t6, t323, t390, t107 –  
 never t76.

• NT120 → 't63' (one word) or NT16 NT6 (two words)  
 NT6 can emit only t154, never t76.  
 Hence NT120 cannot finish with t76 either.

Thus, in every legal derivation the word that immediately precedes the final `t309`
must be one of  
t270, t6, t242, t347, t319, t274, t399, t79, t183, t353, t108, t154, t323, t390, t107.

In the given string the word before the last one is t76 — a value that none of the
candidates above can generate.

Therefore no derivation of the grammar can produce the required suffix “… t76 t309”, and the whole string is not in the language.

No

In this grammar the start symbol S can be rewritten only in one of the following two ways:

1. S → NT72 NT90  
   NT90 → NT83 NT4  

2. S → NT119 NT57  
   NT57 → NT74 NT4  

Hence, in every complete derivation the **right-most symbol of the generated string is produced by NT4**.

The non-terminal NT4 has no further productions except the two terminal rules

NT4 → 't353'  
NT4 → 't309'

Therefore every string generated by the grammar **must end with either t353 or t309**.

The string we have to check ends with t334:

… t261 t334

Since t334 can be produced (for example) by NT31 or NT117, but never by NT4, and NT4 is unavoidably the last symbol derived from S, the given string cannot be generated by the grammar.

No
